    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> <br><br>
<br><br>
Strategy:<br>
<br><br>
Let me start by saying that this deck is based on the common assumption of many people that if you&#39;re not playing Moria, then you&#39;re not using any Balrog support cards.  Since most people just throw one or two Balrogs in their deck as a site 5 safety net, people have started to assume that the Whip and the Sword won&#39;t be played.  With this deck, they are in for a surprise.<br>
<br><br>
The entire strategy of this deck revolves around the Balrog, so I&#39;ll start there.  Every deck has to have an answer to the Balrog now, and there are basically four ways to deal with the Balrog, some being more common than others:  Cancelling skirmishes (Hobbit Stealth, Gandalf&#39;s Staff), Sacrifices (Pippin, Sam, Thrarin), taking it like a Man (armor on Boromir or Aragorn), and (thereotically) beating the Balrog.<br>
<br><br>
Obviously, the Whip can deal with the armor, and so the most popular method of Balrog handling is easily dealt with.  I&#39;m not too worried about people beating the Balrog (especially if I get out the Whip, the Sword or both), but if they do, I&#39;ll tip my cap to them and see if they can beat him again.  The two other options are more difficult.  The Final Cry comes into play here; if they use Gandalf&#39;s Staff to cancel the skirmish, they could quickly be hit with a Final Cry or two, and Gandalf is suddenly hurting.  <br>
<br><br>
There are ways that the opposing fellowship could still get around the Balrog, though, like Staff Asunder, double Hobbit Stealth, or the other option listed above, Sacrificing a weak character like Pip, Sam or Thrarin.  This is where the Uruk-hai come into play.  <br>
<br><br>
Normally, when people see Uruks, they&#39;re not incredibly worried about the Balrog, as site five is a big uruk-hai site and so most uruk decks aren&#39;t big balrog decks.  So then, if early in the game (site two or four usually) the fellowship finds itself in a bind, your opponent will look for his spare hobbits to save Boromir and Aragorn from the Savagery and/or Lurtz&#39; Battle Cry that might be coming.  Force them to lose their sacrificial hobbits early and the balrog with whip is nearly unstoppable.  As a bonus, you could possible get rid of some armor early with the Beyond the Height of Men, just in case you don&#39;t get one of your three whips.  <br>
<br><br>
Site four is CRUCIAL for this deck; you need to wound the fellowhip as much as possible going into site 5 so they have no place to put the wounds when they reach the bridge.  If this combo works, it&#39;s very possible that Frodo could venture to site six all alone.<br>
<br><br>
As for the fellowship, it&#39;s designed to set up quickly, with plenty of weapons, conditions and characters that are played as soon as they reach your hand.  Pippin is there to remove a burden and give his life for the cause.  Boromir and Aragorn often get up to ridiculous strengths (15 or 16 against Nazgul), and so the object is to just keep pace until (hopefully), your shadow wins the game.  However, once everything gets set up, with the Mirror out, and Legolas and Rumil for archery support, this deck is also very capable of mowing through many types of shadow.  And, oh by the way, Secret Sentinels rules.  It&#39;s worth the Elf ally package just to be able to use that card.<br>
<br><br>
Early in the game, you want to move slowly with this deck; you don&#39;t double move until your two fighters are sufficiently pumped up and you have some archery help.  Whether you should go first or second is really up to you; since you have to hold several balrog cards in your hand til site five, it&#39;s helpful to have your opponent getting to site five first, but if you think you can&#39;t risk not getting aragorn out, then bid two, remove one with Pippin, and go get Aragorn.<br>
<br><br>
This deck should work most of the time, although I realize there is always the possibility of a horrible draw.  That&#39;s the chance every deck takes, though, and few offer such high reward potential as this one.<br>
<br>
